<p>Ruby has a #sort method that makes it easy to sort an array. The goal of this exercise is to implement your own sort from scratch (without using Ruby's #sort method!)</p>
<p>
The approach you will implement is called bubble sort. First you examine the first two items in the array. If the second is smaller than the first, you swap their positions. Then you move on to the next two items and keep repeating. You can see a visual of it in action below.
<div>
  <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c8/Bubble-sort-example-300px.gif">
</div>
</p>
<p>
Your job is to implement a bubble sort that takes an array and returns a sorted array. To be clear, you're not allowed to use the built in #sort method - instead you'll write code to go through the array two items at a time to accomplish the same thing.
</p>
              
